---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="GNSS as a Timing Source">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/timing">Timing</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>GNSS as a Timing Source</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Timing · Article 1 of 5</span>
        <h1>GNSS as a Timing Source</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Your phone knows the time to within a microsecond. Every 4G base station in the world
          is synchronised to nanoseconds. The backbone of this global timekeeping infrastructure
          is GNSS — specifically, the atomic clocks aboard satellites 20,000 km overhead.
          This article explains how satellite timing works and why GNSS became the world's
          primary time distribution system.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#atomic-clocks">Atomic clocks aboard satellites</a></li>
          <li><a href="#timing-signal">How timing information is broadcast</a></li>
          <li><a href="#receiver-timing">How a receiver extracts time</a></li>
          <li><a href="#accuracy">Timing accuracy</a></li>
          <li><a href="#why-gnss">Why GNSS dominates time distribution</a></li>
          <li><a href="#vulnerabilities">Vulnerabilities of GNSS timing</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="atomic-clocks">Atomic clocks aboard satellites</h2>
      <p>
        Each GPS satellite carries between two and four atomic clocks — a mix of rubidium
        and caesium oscillators, with Block III satellites also carrying advanced rubidium
        atomic frequency standards (RAFS) and experimental optical clocks. These are not
        the caesium fountain clocks used in national metrology labs, but they are remarkably
        precise for their size and operating environment.
      </p>

      <div class="clock-table">
        <div class="ct-row ct-header">
          <span>Clock type</span>
          <span>Stability (Allan deviation, 1 day)</span>
          <span>Satellites</span>
          <span>Daily drift</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span><strong>Rubidium (Rb)</strong></span>
          <span class="good">~10⁻¹³ – 10⁻¹⁴</span>
          <span>GPS Block IIR/IIR-M, BeiDou, QZSS</span>
          <span>&lt;10 ns/day</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span><strong>Caesium (Cs)</strong></span>
          <span class="good">~10⁻¹³ – 10⁻¹⁴</span>
          <span>GPS Block II/IIA, GLONASS</span>
          <span>&lt;10 ns/day</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span><strong>RAFS (advanced Rb)</strong></span>
          <span class="ok">~10⁻¹⁴</span>
          <span>GPS Block IIF, Block III</span>
          <span>&lt;3 ns/day</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span><strong>Passive hydrogen maser</strong></span>
          <span class="ok">~10⁻¹⁵</span>
          <span>Galileo FOC satellites</span>
          <span>&lt;1 ns/day</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        To put this in perspective: a caesium clock with stability of 10⁻¹³ loses or gains
        less than <strong>1 nanosecond every 10 seconds</strong>. Over a day it drifts by at
        most ~10 ns. Galileo's hydrogen maser clocks are ten times better still — drifting
        less than 1 ns per day. For comparison, a typical quartz oscillator drifts ~1 ms/day.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔬</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Galileo's PHM advantage:</strong> Galileo is the first civil GNSS constellation
          to carry passive hydrogen maser (PHM) clocks. PHMs are significantly more stable than
          rubidium or caesium at averaging times longer than ~1,000 seconds, which improves
          Galileo's broadcast clock accuracy and reduces the satellite clock error contribution
          to user ranging errors.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="timing-signal">How timing information is broadcast</h2>
      <p>
        Each satellite continuously broadcasts a timing signal that allows any receiver to
        determine the exact time of transmission. The mechanism is built into the signal
        structure itself — the ranging code doubles as a timing reference.
      </p>

      <ol class="steps">
        <li>
          <strong>Code epoch markers:</strong> The GPS C/A code repeats every 1 millisecond.
          Each repetition is a precise time marker — the rising edge of the code epoch is
          synchronised to GPS system time to within nanoseconds.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Navigation message subframes:</strong> GPS transmits 5 subframes of 300 bits
          at 50 bps. Each subframe begins with a Telemetry Word (TLM) and a Handover Word (HOW)
          that contains the Time of Week (TOW) — the number of 6-second intervals since
          the start of the GPS week (Sunday midnight GPS time).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Clock correction parameters:</strong> The navigation message broadcasts
          polynomial coefficients (a₀, a₁, a₂) that describe the satellite clock's deviation
          from GPS system time. The receiver applies these to correct the broadcast time.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>UTC offset:</strong> The navigation message also broadcasts the GPS-UTC
          offset (integer leap seconds) and the subnanosecond fractional offset, allowing
          the receiver to compute UTC directly.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <!-- Signal timing diagram -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">GPS timing signal hierarchy</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 200" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr8" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
              <path d="M2 1L8 5L2 9" fill="none" stroke="context-stroke" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>
          <!-- Layers -->
          <rect x="40" y="20" width="600" height="36" rx="6" fill="rgba(0,212,170,0.08)" stroke="rgba(0,212,170,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="340" y="42" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)" font-weight="500">GPS system time — maintained by Master Control Station (MCS), Schriever AFB</text>

          <rect x="40" y="76" width="600" height="36" rx="6" fill="rgba(0,153,255,0.08)" stroke="rgba(0,153,255,0.25)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="340" y="98" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--sans)" font-weight="500">Satellite atomic clock — steered to GPS time, correction broadcast in nav message</text>

          <rect x="40" y="132" width="600" height="36" rx="6" fill="rgba(251,191,36,0.08)" stroke="rgba(251,191,36,0.25)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="340" y="154" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="#fbbf24" font-family="var(--sans)" font-weight="500">Receiver clock — cheap quartz, offset estimated as 4th unknown in nav solution</text>

          <!-- Arrows -->
          <line x1="340" y1="56" x2="340" y2="74" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="1" marker-end="url(#arr8)"/>
          <line x1="340" y1="112" x2="340" y2="130" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="1" marker-end="url(#arr8)"/>

          <!-- Labels -->
          <text x="360" y="68" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">clock correction coefficients</text>
          <text x="360" y="124" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">estimated from pseudoranges</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="receiver-timing">How a receiver extracts time</h2>
      <p>
        A GNSS receiver can determine time in two modes depending on whether it is computing
        position simultaneously:
      </p>

      <div class="timing-modes">
        <div class="tm-card">
          <div class="tm-title">Positioning mode (standard)</div>
          <div class="tm-desc">
            The receiver tracks ≥4 satellites and solves the navigation solution for
            (x, y, z, δt). The receiver clock offset δt is estimated simultaneously
            with position. Time accuracy is limited by the ranging noise and satellite
            clock quality — typically <strong>100 ns to 1 µs</strong> for standard receivers.
          </div>
          <div class="tm-accuracy">~100 ns – 1 µs (1σ)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tm-card tm-timing">
          <div class="tm-title">Timing mode (known position)</div>
          <div class="tm-desc">
            If the receiver position is known (surveyed-in), only the clock offset δt
            needs to be estimated. All available satellites contribute to a single
            clock estimate — an overdetermined system of n equations in 1 unknown.
            Averaging over many satellites and epochs dramatically reduces noise.
            This is how timing receivers achieve <strong>10–50 ns accuracy</strong>.
          </div>
          <div class="tm-accuracy">~10 – 50 ns (1σ)</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The most accurate GNSS timing technique is <strong>common-view timing</strong> —
        two separated receivers simultaneously observe the same satellite. The satellite
        clock error cancels in the difference, leaving only the relative clock offset between
        the two receivers. Used by national metrology laboratories to compare atomic clocks
        across continents with sub-nanosecond precision.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="accuracy">Timing accuracy</h2>
      <p>
        GNSS timing accuracy is specified in the same performance standards as positioning.
        The GPS SPS Performance Standard guarantees:
      </p>

      <div class="accuracy-cards">
        <div class="ac-card">
          <div class="ac-value">≤ 30 ns</div>
          <div class="ac-label">UTC(USNO) offset (95%)</div>
          <div class="ac-note">GPS SPS specification. Typical performance is significantly better.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ac-card ac-highlight">
          <div class="ac-value">~5 – 15 ns</div>
          <div class="ac-label">Typical single-frequency timing (1σ)</div>
          <div class="ac-note">Good antenna, surveyed position, quality timing receiver in steady state.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ac-card">
          <div class="ac-value">&lt; 1 ns</div>
          <div class="ac-label">Common-view / carrier-phase timing</div>
          <div class="ac-note">Used by national metrology labs. Requires long averaging and phase measurements.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The primary error sources for GNSS timing (compared to positioning) are different.
        Multipath affects both. But the dominant timing error is usually the
        <strong>antenna cable delay</strong> — a 1-metre coaxial cable introduces ~5 ns of
        delay. This must be calibrated and entered into the receiver for accurate absolute timing.
        For relative timing (two receivers comparing to each other) the cable delay cancels.
      </p>

      <div class="error-budget-timing">
        <div class="ebt-title">Timing error budget — single-frequency surveyed-position receiver</div>
        <div class="ebt-rows">
          <div class="ebt-row">
            <div class="ebt-source">Satellite clock (broadcast)</div>
            <div class="ebt-bar"><div class="ebt-fill" style="width:35%; background:rgba(251,191,36,0.5);">~5 ns</div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="ebt-row">
            <div class="ebt-source">Ionospheric delay (L1, modelled)</div>
            <div class="ebt-bar"><div class="ebt-fill" style="width:30%; background:rgba(255,71,87,0.4);">~5 ns</div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="ebt-row">
            <div class="ebt-source">Tropospheric delay (modelled)</div>
            <div class="ebt-bar"><div class="ebt-fill" style="width:10%; background:rgba(240,165,0,0.4);">~1 ns</div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="ebt-row">
            <div class="ebt-source">Multipath</div>
            <div class="ebt-bar"><div class="ebt-fill" style="width:15%; background:rgba(163,230,53,0.4);">~3 ns</div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="ebt-row">
            <div class="ebt-source">Receiver noise</div>
            <div class="ebt-bar"><div class="ebt-fill" style="width:10%; background:rgba(0,212,170,0.4);">~1 ns</div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="ebt-total">Combined (RSS): ~8 ns typical · Specification: ≤30 ns (95%)</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="why-gnss">Why GNSS dominates time distribution</h2>
      <p>
        Before GNSS, distributing precise time over long distances was genuinely hard.
        Methods included telephone time signals, Loran-C radio navigation, and physically
        transporting caesium clocks between laboratories (portable clock comparisons).
        GNSS changed everything:
      </p>

      <div class="advantage-grid">
        <div class="adv-card">
          <div class="adv-icon">🌍</div>
          <div class="adv-title">Global coverage</div>
          <div class="adv-desc">Nanosecond-accurate time is available anywhere with a clear sky view — remote oil platforms, ships at sea, mountain observatories, Antarctic research stations.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="adv-card">
          <div class="adv-icon">💰</div>
          <div class="adv-title">Near-zero cost</div>
          <div class="adv-desc">A timing-capable GNSS receiver costs £50–£500. The satellite infrastructure is paid for by national governments. The time signal is free to all users.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="adv-card">
          <div class="adv-icon">🔗</div>
          <div class="adv-title">Traceable to atomic standards</div>
          <div class="adv-desc">GPS time is steered to UTC(USNO) — the US Naval Observatory's atomic time standard. The offset is broadcast in the navigation message. GNSS timing is formally traceable to national standards.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="adv-card">
          <div class="adv-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="adv-title">Simultaneous multi-point distribution</div>
          <div class="adv-desc">The same signal synchronises millions of receivers simultaneously — impossible with wired or point-to-point distribution methods. Critical for large-scale infrastructure like cellular networks.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="vulnerabilities">Vulnerabilities of GNSS timing</h2>
      <p>
        The same properties that make GNSS an excellent timing source also create
        dependencies and vulnerabilities that critical infrastructure operators must understand:
      </p>

      <div class="vuln-list">
        <div class="vuln">
          <div class="vuln-title">RF interference and jamming</div>
          <div class="vuln-desc">
            GNSS signals arrive at ground level at approximately −130 dBm — about 20 dB below
            the thermal noise floor of a receiver. A modest jammer can disrupt GNSS reception
            over hundreds of square kilometres. Timing loss can propagate to thousands of
            downstream systems (telecom base stations, NTP servers) within seconds.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="vuln">
          <div class="vuln-title">Spoofing</div>
          <div class="vuln-desc">
            A spoofing attack broadcasts counterfeit GNSS signals that gradually shift the
            receiver's time and position estimate without triggering alarms. A timing spoof
            can cause financial timestamps to drift, cellular handovers to fail, or power
            grid synchrophasors to report false phase angles. Detection requires signal
            monitoring or multi-constellation cross-checking.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="vuln">
          <div class="vuln-title">Space weather</div>
          <div class="vuln-desc">
            Severe geomagnetic storms (G4–G5, Kp ≥ 8) can cause ionospheric scintillation
            that interrupts satellite signal lock, and solar radio bursts can directly jam
            GNSS frequencies. The October 2003 Halloween storms temporarily disrupted GPS
            timing services globally. See the <a href="/dashboards/space-weather">Space Weather dashboard</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="vuln">
          <div class="vuln-title">Single point of failure</div>
          <div class="vuln-desc">
            Critical infrastructure that relies solely on GNSS timing is vulnerable to any
            GNSS outage. Best practice is to maintain a backup timing source — typically a
            GPSDO (GPS-disciplined oscillator) that can holdover for hours using its internal
            oscillator, or an independent time source such as eLoran or a direct atomic clock.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Real-world impact:</strong> In January 2016, a GPS control segment error
          caused a 13-microsecond timing offset that propagated to hundreds of telecom base
          stations and caused synchronisation failures across several national mobile networks.
          In 2019, a software fault on a single GPS satellite broadcast incorrect timing data
          for 13 hours before being detected. These incidents highlight why resilient
          backup timing is essential for critical infrastructure.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚛️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Atomic clocks in orbit</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Each satellite carries 2–4 atomic clocks (Rb, Cs, or hydrogen maser). Stability of 10⁻¹³ to 10⁻¹⁵ — drifting less than 10 ns/day. Galileo's PHMs are the most precise civil space clocks ever deployed.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Time embedded in the signal</div>
          <div class="summary-body">The ranging code epoch and TOW field in the navigation message carry precise time to every receiver. Clock correction coefficients in the nav message correct satellite clock drift to &lt;1 m equivalent range.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⏱️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">10–50 ns timing accuracy</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Standard timing receivers achieve 10–50 ns (1σ) with surveyed position. Cable delay calibration is essential for absolute accuracy. Common-view timing achieves sub-nanosecond for laboratory comparisons.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚠️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Vulnerability requires backup</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Jamming, spoofing and space weather can disrupt GNSS timing with cascading effects on dependent infrastructure. Critical systems require holdover-capable GPSDOs and independent backup timing sources.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/timing" class="nav-prev">← Timing</a>
        <a href="/learn/timing/time-scales" class="nav-next">Time Scales →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>GPS SPS Performance Standard, 5th Edition (2020). <a href="https://www.gps.gov/technical/ps/2020-SPS-performance-standard.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GPS.gov →</a></li>
          <li>Lombardi, M. A. (2008). The use of GPS disciplined oscillators as primary frequency standards for calibration and metrology laboratories. <em>NCSLI Measure</em>, 3(3), 56–65.</li>
          <li>Lewandowski, W. & Thomas, C. (1991). GPS time transfer. <em>Proceedings of the IEEE</em>, 79(7), 991–1000.</li>
          <li>Teunissen, P. J. G. & Montenbruck, O. (eds.) (2017). <em>Springer Handbook of Global Navigation Satellite Systems</em>. Chapter 25 — GNSS Timing.</li>
          <li>USNO GPS timing information. <a href="https://www.usno.navy.mil/USNO/time/gps" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">usno.navy.mil →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout-warn { background: rgba(251,191,36,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(251,191,36,0.2); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout strong { color: var(--text); }

  /* Clock table */
  .clock-table { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .ct-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 160px 200px 1fr 100px; gap: 10px; padding: 10px 14px; background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; font-size: 13px; align-items: center; }
  .ct-header { font-size: 10px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text3); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; font-family: var(--mono); background: var(--bg3); }
  .good { color: var(--accent); font-family: var(--mono); }
  .ok { color: #a3e635; font-family: var(--mono); }

  /* Diagram */
  .diagram-wrap { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px; margin: 24px 0; }
  .diagram-label { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; margin-bottom: 12px; }

  /* Steps */
  .steps { counter-reset: step; list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 16px 0; }
  .steps li { counter-increment: step; padding: 12px 12px 12px 48px; position: relative; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 14px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; }
  .steps li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .steps li::before { content: counter(step); position: absolute; left: 12px; top: 14px; width: 22px; height: 22px; background: rgba(0,212,170,0.12); color: var(--accent); border-radius: 50%; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-family: var(--mono); }

  /* Timing modes */
  .timing-modes { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .tm-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 18px; }
  .tm-timing { border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.3); }
  .tm-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .tm-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .tm-accuracy { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--accent); }

  /* Accuracy cards */
  .accuracy-cards { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: 12px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .ac-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 18px; text-align: center; }
